\begin_layout Subsubsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the loss forecasting model to simulate the credit card portfolio
 under different economics scenarios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also built the risk appetite framework, which are the maximum Loss we
 are willing to suffer in the recession.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Background: TOO BIG TO FAIL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
This exercise is required by
\series default
 the Federal Reserve, our regulators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
BECAUSE
\series default
 in the good time, like now, banks 
\series bold
tend
\series default
 to take higher risk, for example booking the low FICO customers,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
with the idea
\series default
 that if the crisis comes, they know the government will come to 
\series bold
SAVE
\series default
 them,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
because
\series default
 they are deeply rooted into the economy system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is how we call too big to fail, or in economic theory, moral hazard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
IN DETAIL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
So every quarter Federal Reserve will give us 3 economic scenarios, baseline,
 adverse and severely adverse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And we 
\series bold
plug in
\series default
 those scenarios into our model to 
\series bold
test the sensitivity
\series default
 of our portfolio to economic macro factors,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The goal is to insure that
\series default
 if another financial crisis happens tomorrow 
\series bold
un-expectedly
\series default
, then we have enough capital to survive through it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
SUMMARY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So our job is to insure our portfolio is 
\series bold
health enough today
\series default
 so that tomorrow when crisis happens when can survive by ourselves, 
\series bold
no need the taxpayer's money!
\end_layout

