\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Modelling part of the job
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "the-modelling-part-of-the-job"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use a weekly initial unemployment insurance claim (weekly IUIC) as our
 macro input, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We saw it dropped from 350 thousand to 250 thousand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But our loss forecasting goes up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So I was assigned to this job to investigate why this counter-intuitive
 thing happens
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turned out to be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our model, we didn't use the IUIC itself, we use the change of IUIC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But so as the actual IUIC dropped from 350 to 250, but the baseline scenario
 that Fed gave us, is always stabilize at 270,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So previously, we have a positive gap between actual and forecasting, thus
 a positive impact, now as the situation improves, we turned out to have
 a negative gap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The takeaway is: ???
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Probably the sensitivity between our portfolio to the change of IUIC is
 not constant, what I mean is the coefficient of the change of IUIC may
 be not constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It may be dependent on the level of IUIC itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the IUIC level is low, the sensitivity is low.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we probably want to incorporate the level of IUIC, rather than only the
 change of IUIC.
\end_layout

